<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-33-0425 </DOCNO><TEXT>The export of hazards to developing countries, frequently associated withthe transfer of technology, is an increasing public health problem. Itmay arise from the export of hazardous products and wastes, or from thetransfer of hazardous industries in the absence of appropriate safeguards.Multinational corporations bear a major responsibility for having lowerstandards of health protection in manufacturing and marketing in thedeveloping countries than in home-country operations. These firms arecoming under growing international pressure from concerned citizens,unions, environmental groups, national governments and internationalorganizations, religious groups, the media, and public health professionals.</TEXT></DOC>